Gatanga MP Nduati Ngugi projects that at this rate, by 2023, the value will have risen to between Sh6 million and Sh24 million as accrued investments take shape. 

Rates for a single room rental have started improving from between Sh800 and Sh2,000 to between Sh1,200 and Sh3,000 in the towns. 






According to Mr Simon Kihara, the chairman of Kiambu Property Investment Link Company, which has pitched camp at Njabini, most expressions of interest involve investors who want to put up entertainment joints and residential gated communities. 

“From Gataka-ini all the way to Njabini is the Aberdare Forest and along the way is a fish camp … where investors placing bids are anticipating an opportunity for tourism,” he told the Nation. 

Most bids are in Gatanga Sub-County, where land is available in bigger portions as compared to Njabini township, where the land is already subdivided into plots. 

“In Gatanga, it is very possible to get land in one- and five-acre packages, and once bought and subdivided into plots, the gain for investors hits the roof. Others want land in at least three-acre packages where they can invest in hotels and lounges as well as camp sites,” he said. 

Mombasa hoteliers 

Mr Ngugi said there were bids from three Mombasa hoteliers seeking temporary leases to build tourist hotels at the Aberdare Forest stretch between Gataka-ini and Njabini. 



