“Other opportunities that we will have are establishment of gas stations, exhibitions to showcase Gatanga musical talent, tour operators capitalising on selling the Ndakaini dam, vast tea plantations and rich culture as tourist attraction opportunities,” he said. 

Area County Commissioner Mohammed Barre said the road is one of President Uhuru Kenyatta’s legacy projects, which must be delivered within schedule and be of high quality. 

“The President is very much concerned that this road be delivered since it has been long overdue in fulfilling the wish of Murang’a and Nyandarua people to get linked,” he said, adding that once complete, the returns should easily reach Sh15 billion annually by 2025. 

The road is expected to open up the region to Machakos, Garissa, Kitui and Nakuru counties. 

Travelling from Gatanga to Njabini will cost Sh80, from the current Sh250. 

As Henan Highway Construction Company earthmovers continue to implement the project, property brokers are all over the place linking buyers to juicy deals. 






Benefits 

Immediate direct benefits include employment of at least 500 youths and about 20 new small businesses, including sale of food and drinks, supply of culverts and investment consultancies being established in the area. Landlords will tap into the market provided by workers engaged in the project.  



