Mr Ngugi said the project has breathed a new lease of life into dormant towns that are now awash with speculative property investors buying any available space. 

“So good is land business in this area that the multiplying factor by the time the project is delivered in the next 36 months is billed to rise steadily to rest at six times the principal investment. I urge interested land buyers in this area to be very vigilant and apply due diligence since we also know there are crooks,” he said. 

Area Directorate of Criminal Investigations boss John Kanda told the Nation that he has categorised land related crimes as among resultant effects of the huge interest investors have expressed in land in the area. 

“We want to assure all involved that we are working round the clock to ensure that such a high economic value project does not get transformed into a slaughter house for investors through fraudulent land deals. While we urge all to exercise due diligence before committing themselves to deals, we will remain vigilant and round up all crooks,” he said. 

